│[1m [0m[1mpatch_description       [0m[1m [0m│ The current approach optimizes circle positions randomly, but doesn't leverage the key    │
│[1m                          [0m│ insight that optimal packings use variable-sized circles strategically. I propose:        │
│[1m                          [0m│                                                                                           │
│[1m                          [0m│ 1. Replace the structured ring initialization with a greedy algorithm that places circles │
│[1m                          [0m│ incrementally, prioritizing positions that allow larger radii                             │
│[1m                          [0m│ 2. Make the relaxation radius-aware: larger circles should contribute more to repulsion   │
│[1m                          [0m│ forces                                                                                    │
│[1m                          [0m│ 3. Implement a two-phase approach: first get good spatial distribution, then fine-tune    │
│[1m                          [0m│ with explicit radius optimization                                                         │
│[1m                          [0m│ 4. Add a phase that spreads circles toward boundaries (corners/edges give more room for   │
│[1m                          [0m│ radii due to wall constraints)                                                            │
│[1m                          [0m│                                                                                           │
│[1m                          [0m│ This should substantially improve packing density by ensuring high-value (large-radius)   │
│[1m                          [0m│ circles get priority placement.                                                           │
